---
import ScenariosLayout from '../../layouts/ScenariosLayout.astro';

const countries = [
  {
    id:'united-states', title:'United States', gdp:'$28.8T', tag:'winner', tagColor:'#10b981',
    summary:'Net petroleum exporter since 2020 (record 2.8M b/d, 13.6M b/d production). Only ~2% via Hormuz — insulated on physical supply, benefits from reserve-currency safe-haven inflows. SPR ~409M bbl plus >170M bbl exchange program.',
    energy:'Net exporter; 2025 net exports record ~2.8M b/d; production 13.6M b/d. Only ~0.5M b/d from Gulf (~2% of consumption). Shale ~65% of output.',
    food:'Large net food/ag exporter. Fertilizer ~12% from Gulf — second-order input-cost channel. Domestic vulnerability LOW.',
    trade:'Negligible direct Gulf routing. Indirect via global container-rate inflation (+25-35%).',
    financial:'Reserve-currency safe-haven beneficiary. Key risk: inflation channel forcing Fed tightening. Goldman raised recession probability to 30%.',
    substitution:'Shale: ~9 months new well. SPR ~409M bbl. >170M bbl exchange program. Substantial cushion.',
    hormuz:'Brent +55% to ~$112-120; physical supply intact; shale margins expand; SPR deployed. CPI +1-2pp risk.',
    strike:'Shale + SPR + Canadian supply insulate; price-driven inflation manageable.',
    cable:'Relatively insulated; transatlantic/transpacific routes unaffected.',
    ceasefire:'Brent reverts; shale margins compress; SPR refill. Gives back windfall, no lasting damage.',
    history:'Each cycle the US grows more insulated as production rises. 1973: devastating. 2022: net beneficiary.',
    secondOrder:'Simultaneously administering the blockade and benefiting from elevated prices. US LNG at 57% of EU imports, locking in long-term market share.',
    confidence:'high',
  },
  {
    id:'china', title:'China', gdp:'$18.5T', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Largest Hormuz oil user (26.9% of Q1 2025 flows) and Iran\'s #1 customer (~1.37M b/d). Best-prepared loser: ~1.4B bbl reserves (~121 days) and Russian ESPO pipeline bypass.',
    energy:'Crude imports 11.6M b/d. 45-50% transit Hormuz. Iran #1 customer ~1.37M b/d. Hedge: Russia (ESPO pipeline bypasses Hormuz), Kazakhstan/Central Asia.',
    food:'Grain self-sufficient (706.5M tonnes). Soybean ~15% self-sufficient but routes (Brazil/US) non-Hormuz.',
    trade:'Heavy Gulf energy + Asia-Europe goods. Red Sea rerouting +10-15 days, +40% fuel, freight +149%. Belt & Road exposed.',
    financial:'CNY pressured by import bill. PBOC manages with ~$3.2T FX reserves. Petroyuan marginally advanced.',
    substitution:'~1.4B bbl reserves (~121 days). Russia ESPO + Central Asia bypass Hormuz. Reserves cushion ~3-4 months.',
    hormuz:'~5-5.8M b/d at risk + ~1.37M b/d Iranian crude cut. Draws reserves; ramps Russian ESPO. GDP drag if >3-4 months.',
    strike:'Reserves + Russian crude backfill; price shock bigger channel than volume.',
    cable:'Direct hit — SMW4/PEACE systems; ~25% Asia-Europe traffic; latency surge.',
    ceasefire:'Strong winner: Iranian barrels resume; import bill falls; likely "buys the dip" to restock.',
    history:'2022: bought discounted Russian/Iranian crude, accelerated stockpiling. $100B+ invested in Iranian infrastructure now at risk — "trapped creditor" dynamic.',
    secondOrder:'$100B Iranian investment creates trapped-creditor dynamic. Chinese refiners pivot to Brazilian pre-salt; Gulf crude market share in China\'s basket falls structurally.',
    confidence:'high',
  },
  {
    id:'european-union', title:'European Union', gdp:'$18.3T', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Incomplete post-Russia pivot: ~7% of LNG via Hormuz (Qatar), gas storage at record low ~28% (Mar 2026). Germany in deepest manufacturing recession. ECB forced to hike into weakness. ECB severe scenario: +6.3pp cumulative inflation.',
    energy:'>140 bcm LNG in 2025 (US 56-58%, Qatar 8.9%). ~7% via Hormuz. Gas storage 38% vs 55% seasonal norm. France insulated via nuclear.',
    food:'Broadly cereal-secure. Gas-price spikes hit nitrogen-fertilizer production (ammonia is gas-intensive).',
    trade:'Most Red Sea/Suez-exposed economy. Cape rerouting: +10-15 days, freight +149% (5x spike).',
    financial:'ECB held at 2.00%; expected hike June 2026. Growth cut to 1.1%, inflation 3.1%. Italy spread-widening risk.',
    substitution:'Slowest. US LNG 56-58%, near saturation. Nuclear (France), renewables (48% of EU electricity 2025). Multi-quarter levers.',
    hormuz:'Loses ~7% LNG; TTF + power spike; German manufacturing recession deepens; ECB forced to hike. Storage deficit -17.6pp.',
    strike:'Oil-price channel compounds industrial-cost squeeze.',
    cable:'IMEWE/SMW4/PEACE land in Europe; ~25% Asia-Europe data at risk; Frankfurt/Paris latency.',
    ceasefire:'Largest relief beneficiary: gas/oil fall, manufacturing recovers, ECB can ease, EUR stabilizes. Most to gain from de-escalation.',
    history:'1973 drove France\'s nuclear plan. 2022: Russia cut gas, TTF >€300/MWh, REPowerEU €300B. 2026 tests incomplete transition.',
    secondOrder:'Stagflation trap — energy shock raises inflation while crushing demand. Having diversified from Russian gas into Qatar LNG, EU finds Qatar LNG also transits a war zone.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'japan', title:'Japan', gdp:'$4.2T', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Highest G7 Hormuz dependency: ~93-96% crude from Middle East. Double-hit via energy bill and weak yen (2022: record ¥20T trade deficit). Deepest strategic stockpile: 483M bbl combined (263M govt + 220M industry). Rice stockpile: only ~15 days.',
    energy:'2.36M b/d crude; ~94% from Middle East; ~93% via Hormuz — highest of any major economy. LNG: Australia >40%, only ~6-20% via Hormuz.',
    food:'~38% caloric self-sufficiency. Rice stockpile: only ~15 days (May 2026). Fertilizer/feed-grain import reliance >90%.',
    trade:'Energy is dominant Gulf-routed flow. Cape rerouting +3,500 nm / 10-14 days.',
    financial:'Yen is key transmission. 2022: import bill nearly doubled; record ¥20T deficit; yen 109.8→131.4/USD.',
    substitution:'483M bbl reserves (~166 days combined). Largest-ever SPR release executing. Refinery rigidity caps fast crude-grade switching.',
    hormuz:'~93% of oil at risk; reserves cover ~166 days but grade-constrained; acute yen pressure. Crude imports fell 50% since onset.',
    strike:'Import bill flows straight through; SPR cushions volume, not price.',
    cable:'Lower direct hit; financial-data latency to EU rises.',
    ceasefire:'Strong relief rally; yen and import bill normalize; SPR-refill demand supports crude.',
    history:'1973: 90% ME-dependent, 55-day stockpile, GDP -7%. Built 90-day-minimum regime now at 483M bbl. 2026 most severe since 1973.',
    secondOrder:'Entire petrochemical and LPG supply chain depends on Gulf NGL/LPG (>70% of Japan\'s LPG). Plus rice stockpile depletion to ~15 days — potential political crisis alongside energy crisis.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'india', title:'India', gdp:'$3.9T', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Triple hit: 88.6% crude-import-dependent (~40% via Hormuz), Gulf supplying 20-30% of urea, fertilizer subsidy blowing to ₹1.92 lakh crore, plus ~$49B Gulf remittance corridor at risk. $691B reserves and Russian-crude hedge (31.5%) mitigate. 220,000+ nationals repatriated.',
    energy:'88.6% crude-import-dependent. Russia 31.5%. ~40% via Hormuz. Russian crude (non-Hormuz) is structural hedge.',
    food:'Grain self-sufficient. ~60% edible oil imported. Gulf supplies 20-30% urea, 30% DAP. Subsidy ₹1.92 lakh crore, could breach ₹3 lakh crore.',
    trade:'Heavy Gulf/Red Sea routing. Cape rerouting +$300/container + 10-14 days.',
    financial:'Rupee 85.6→93.2/USD. $691B reserves. Remittances $129B, ~38% from GCC (~$49B). 220,000+ repatriated.',
    substitution:'Moderate-fast on crude (Russia pivot proven). Slow on fertilizer. Remittance = second-order Hormuz transmission unique to India.',
    hormuz:'~40% crude + 20-30% urea at risk; subsidy spikes; rupee pressure; $49B remittance corridor disrupted.',
    strike:'Brent >$120 pushes CAD to 2.1%, subsidy +14%; inflation hits 1.4B.',
    cable:'Directly in Red Sea cut cluster (SMW4, IMEWE, FALCON); 70% of Europe-bound data.',
    ceasefire:'Sharp relief: rupee stabilizes, subsidy eases, remittances resume.',
    history:'1990-91: evacuated 175,000+ from Kuwait; BoP crisis — forex $1.2B, pledged 67t gold. 2022: pivoted to Russian crude. Playbook re-run.',
    secondOrder:'Gulf remittance corridor freeze — ~9M nationals in GCC representing ~$49B/year. If GCC economies collapse, removes India\'s single largest external income source. More macro-significant than direct oil exposure.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'saudi-arabia', title:'Saudi Arabia', gdp:'$1.1T', tag:'winner', tagColor:'#10b981',
    summary:'Only economy net-long a Hormuz closure: 2-3M b/d spare + East-West pipeline (7M b/d to Yanbu). Captures price windfall while rivals blocked. Offsets: ~$90-96/bbl fiscal breakeven, infrastructure risk (IRGC struck Manifa/Khurais/pumping station April), Yanbu loading bottleneck ~4-4.5M b/d.',
    energy:'Swing producer. Spare 2-3M b/d. Petroline 7M b/d to Yanbu (Red Sea bypass). Yanbu loads ~4-4.5M b/d (bottleneck). PIF >$1.15T.',
    food:'Heavy importer (~80%+). Strategic wheat ~4 months. Energy-cost-insulated as producer.',
    trade:'Crude exits via Red Sea (Yanbu) bypassing Hormuz — structural advantage.',
    financial:'Riyal pegged 3.75/USD. IMF breakeven ~$90-96/bbl. Revenue captures ~75-80% of each incremental $/bbl.',
    substitution:'Fastest pivot — output in 30 days, reroute via Petroline. The swing supplier.',
    hormuz:'Biggest winner — exports via Petroline while rivals blocked. Risk: own infrastructure targeted (proven April 2026).',
    strike:'Pipeline attacked and restored to full capacity April 2026 — resilience demonstrated but vulnerable.',
    cable:'Jeddah cut epicenter (SMW4/IMEWE). Vision 2030 data-hub exposed.',
    ceasefire:'Price normalizes to $60-65; windfall evaporates; fiscal-deficit returns; Vision 2030 gap reopens.',
    history:'1973: $3→$12. 1990: 5.1M to 8.5M b/d, captured windfall. $25-50B added annual revenue estimated in 2026.',
    secondOrder:'Yanbu bottleneck caps monopoly power — 2.5-3M b/d arrives with nowhere to load. Creates 6-12 month window for port expansion that would make Saudi structurally more resilient.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'uae', title:'UAE', gdp:'$509B', tag:'mixed', tagColor:'#f59e0b',
    summary:'Only Gulf producer with material bypass (ADCOP 1.8M b/d to Fujairah, doubling by 2027). Crude egress ~57% insulated. But hub functions (JAFZA = 36% of Dubai GDP, DIFC, Emirates, tourism ~13% GDP) cannot be relocated. High-beta loser on escalation, winner on ceasefire.',
    energy:'3.4-3.7M b/d production. ADCOP routes ~57% via Fujairah bypass. West-East expansion doubling by 2027.',
    food:'Imports >90% of food. Russia largest wheat supplier (Black Sea, non-Hormuz). Container leg is the vulnerability.',
    trade:'Non-oil trade $1.03T (2025). JAFZA 36% of Dubai GDP. Jebel Ali is largest ME port. Closure chokes transshipment.',
    financial:'Dubai $255.3B GDP (>95% non-oil). DIFC >4,500 firms. DFM foreign investors 50% of trading. Tourism ~13% GDP ($72.8B).',
    substitution:'HIGH for crude (Fujairah). LOW for hub functions — Jebel Ali, DIFC, Emirates cannot relocate.',
    hormuz:'~43% crude stranded; JAFZA (36% GDP) severely disrupted; tourism and DFM hit. Net GDP drag large despite bypass.',
    strike:'ADNOC revenue benefits if spared; downside if targeted directly.',
    cable:'Acute — regional cloud/data hub; drone strikes on data centers reported. Iran "protection fee" threats.',
    ceasefire:'Strong rebound — tourism, re-exports, DFM/ADX snap back; risk premium compresses.',
    history:'2022: fiscal surpluses, sanctions-adjacent conduit. 2026 is first existential shock to diversification model.',
    secondOrder:'Collapse of Jebel Ali/Dubai re-export model — 36% GDP depends on free goods flow through Hormuz. Sustained closure converts Dubai from global hub to regional destination. 15-24 months to rebuild confidence.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'russia', title:'Russia', gdp:'$2.0T', tag:'winner', tagColor:'#10b981',
    summary:'Clearest beneficiary, zero Hormuz dependency. #2 crude exporter (~4.8M b/d), #1 wheat exporter (~20%), ~18-21% of global fertilizer. Fills every gap simultaneously. Revenue reverses ~24% oil-and-gas budget decline. Structural cost: deepening China dependency.',
    energy:'~4.76M b/d exports (#2 globally, ~11%). Urals discount narrows. Power of Siberia to China +25% to 38.8 bcm.',
    food:'#1 wheat exporter, ~20% share. Fertilizer ~18-21% global, targeting 25% by 2030. Domestic food-secure.',
    trade:'Offensive beneficiary. Any Gulf shock lifts gas-linked ammonia/urea prices — Russia benefits as low-cost producer. Zero Hormuz dependency.',
