    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'brazil', title:'Brazil', gdp:'$2.2T', tag:'winner', tagColor:'#10b981',
    summary:'Structural winner: net crude exporter (record 3.77M b/d, ~80% pre-salt), #1 soy/sugar exporter filling food gaps, ethanol/flex fleet (fuel +10-20% vs 30-40% in US). Cost: fertilizer imports ~70-85%, ~$4.36B/yr Russia-linked. Record April surplus $10.5B.',
    energy:'Net exporter since 2024 (#1 export). 3.77M b/d (+12.3%). Ethanol/flex held fuel to +10-20%. Asian exports +95% to China Q1.',
    food:'#1 net ag exporter; grains >165M tonnes. Fertilizer: imports ~70-85%, 96% potash. Russia 25.8% of imports ($4.36B).',
    trade:'Soybeans 108.68M tonnes (~58% global, ~65% to China). Corn #2. Sugar #1. Gap-filler for disrupted channels.',
    financial:'Free-floating BRL. Commodity boom is BRL-supportive. Record April surplus $10.5B (+37.5%). IMF revised growth upward.',
    substitution:'HIGH on energy (domestic + ethanol). LOW-MODERATE on fertilizer (96% potash reliance).',
    hormuz:'Strong winner: Brent lifts export revenue; food disruption diverts demand to Brazilian soy/corn/sugar. Offset: nitrogen-fertilizer bill.',
    strike:'Winner on oil + ethanol; moderate fertilizer cost rise. Cleanest positive scenario.',
    cable:'Marginal: risk-off EM outflows; commodity logistics intact.',
    ceasefire:'Premia unwind — gives back windfall; planting-cost relief is domestic positive.',
    history:'1973: ~80% oil-dependent, launched Proalcool (1975). Pivot from 1973 victim to 2026 beneficiary is the defining structural shift. Petrobras US exports fell to zero; China at 62%.',
    secondOrder:'Geopolitical repositioning as Asia\'s "neutral" oil supplier. Chinese NOCs pursuing equity stakes in pre-salt blocks. Brazil-China-India oil trade shift could persist for a decade.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'egypt', title:'Egypt', gdp:'$395B', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Highest-stress profile. Hit on all four channels: flipped to net LNG importer (+188%), world\'s #1 wheat importer (~74-80% from Russia) feeding 70M bread subsidy, Suez revenue collapsed -60% ($10.25B→$4B), thin reserves ~$35B under IMF. Largest ceasefire beneficiary.',
    energy:'LNG importer: 9.01M tonnes 2025 (+188%). Domestic gas output -30% since 2021. No export return until ~2030s.',
    food:'#1 wheat importer: ~12.5-14.7M tonnes, ~74-80% from Russia. Bread subsidy: >70M of 105M people. First price hike in 36 years (+300%).',
    trade:'Suez collapsed: $4B vs $10.25B (2023), -60%. A closure re-freezes Suez — the single largest downside.',
    financial:'IMF $8B EFF. ~$35B reserves. External-debt/GDP >42%. 4th currency devaluation since 2022.',
    substitution:'VERY LOW. Cannot replace Suez revenue. Dependent on Gulf deposits + IMF.',
    hormuz:'LNG bill spikes, wheat/freight up, Suez further disrupted. Triple FX drain to crisis risk.',
    strike:'Severe — energy + food inflation; Suez hit.',
    cable:'Major cables transit Suez corridor; Egypt is a cable landing hub.',
    ceasefire:'Only relief path — Suez recovery toward $10B, LNG/wheat ease. Single largest ceasefire-beneficiary.',
    history:'1967: Suez closed, devastated. 2022: wheat dependence exposed, devaluation cycle + IMF. Program predicated on Suez $9B recovery — now invalidated.',
    secondOrder:'Suez permanent re-collapse risk — if Gulf-to-Europe traffic stays on Cape, persistent near-zero revenue. Egypt\'s fiscal math collapses. Social unrest tail risk.',
    confidence:'medium',
  },
  {
    id:'pakistan', title:'Pakistan', gdp:'$338B', tag:'loser', tagColor:'#ef4444',
    summary:'Unique double-Hormuz risk: energy supplier AND ~$38B remittance lifeline are the same region. ~83% oil-import-dependent, Brent-indexed take-or-pay LNG, ~$9.4-14.5B reserves under $7B IMF. KSE-100 -9.57% on March 2. 4-day work week, school closures implemented.',
    energy:'~83% crude from Gulf (Hormuz). 9 Qatari LNG cargoes/month, Brent-indexed take-or-pay. Both crude AND LNG Brent-indexed AND Hormuz-routed.',
    food:'~240M population; inflation peaked 38%. IMF forced subsidy removal — fuel spike directly drives food inflation.',
    trade:'Energy dominant ($15-17B crude + LNG). Deficit financed by remittances.',
    financial:'IMF $7B EFF. Reserves ~$9.4-14.5B (2-3 months). Remittances record ~$38.3B FY25 (+26.6%). First surplus in 14 years — fragile.',
    substitution:'LOW. ~83% import-dependent, take-or-pay LNG, thin reserves. No short-term alternative. Remittance = unique double-Hormuz.',
    hormuz:'Physical supply cut AND price spike on take-or-pay; GCC remittances at risk. 4-day work week, school closures.',
    strike:'Severe energy-bill inflation + food pass-through to 240M. Remittances may hold if Gulf labor intact.',
    cable:'Disrupts remittance-transfer and trade-finance — uniquely damaging. NetBlocks confirmed degradation.',
    ceasefire:'Relief — Brent eases, remittances stabilize, food cools, IMF achievable. Structural fragility persists.',
    history:'1990: workers evacuated from Kuwait, remittances disrupted. 2022: near-default, inflation 38%. 2026: order-of-magnitude larger exposure.',
    secondOrder:'Energy-supplier / remittance-source double collapse — GCC supplies both energy AND remittances that finance it. Self-reinforcing external balance collapse unlike any other economy. IMF conditionality becomes impossible without emergency augmentation.',
